on key works to produce a thorough analysis rather than a survey. Unsettling Narratives opens up an area of scholarship and discussion—the use of postcolonial theories—relatively new to the field of children’s literature and demonstrates that many texts recycle the colonial discourses naturalized within mainstream cultures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutochtones dans la littérature. 0aChildrenxBooks and reading. 0aChildren's literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aChildren's literaturexPolitical aspects. 0aEnfantsxLivres et lecture. 0aIndigenous peoples in literature. 0aLittérature de jeunessexAspect politique. 0aLittérature de jeunessexHistoire et critique. 0aNative peoples in literature. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aPostcolonialisme dans la littérature. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 4aLiterary Criticism: Children’s Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Children's & Young Adult Literature.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458072940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554580729423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554580729/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles